default3. Armed Violence Reduction 
default  
default3.1 
defaultArmed violence threatdefaultensdefault people’s safety and securitydefault, defaultundermines poverty reduction, development, social cohesion, human rights effortsdefault,default and 
defaultresults in over 16 million injuries requiring medical attention each year
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.2 Globally, 
defaulttwo million people livdefaultedefault with firearm injuries sustained in non-conflict settings over the past decadedefault. Research indicates that 
default80% of victims consulted developed a severe disability as a result of their injury and need long term medical and social care
default.
default Their injuries generate considerable direct and indirect costs, including those incurred through treatment, recovery, and lost productivity.  
defaultMany injuries negative
defaultly
default impact
default 
defaulthouseholds, disrupting social
default relations
default and creating 
defaultsevere gender inequalities
default.
default&#xa0;
default3.3 
defaultAn estimated 
default740,000
default people die every year from armed violence
default. 
defaultArmed violence is one of the defaulttop ten causes of death defaultin over 40 countries and the fourth leading cause of death
default for people aged
default 15-
default44 globally.
default defaultFor every person who dies, thousands more are injured.  
defaultOnly by integrating armed violence reduction into development 
defaultactivit
defaulties in a multi-sector process involving multiple 
defaultand diverse actors can stakeholders address the combined local, national, 
defaultand 
defaultregional
default 
defaultfactors which drive armed violence
default. 
